"    <div id=\"topicTitle\">",
"     Patient information: Human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine (The Basics)",
"    </div>",
"    <span class=\"view\">",
"     View in",
"     <a class=\"lang\" href=\"./es-419/human-papillomavirus-hpv-vaccine-the-basics?source=topic_page\">",
"      Spanish",
"     </a>",
"    </span>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"./authors-and-editors/patient-information\">",
"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216790\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is the human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The HPV vaccine helps keep people from getting infected with a germ called &ldquo;human papillomavirus,&rdquo; or &ldquo;HPV.&rdquo;",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Vaccines are treatments that can prevent infections. They work by preparing the body to fight the germs that cause the infections. Vaccines usually come in shots, but some come in nose sprays or medicines that people swallow. Vaccines are also called &ldquo;vaccinations&rdquo; or &ldquo;immunizations.&rdquo;",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216797\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Why should I get the HPV vaccine?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The HPV vaccine can help keep you from getting an HPV infection. An HPV infection can lead to cancer of the cervix (cervical cancer) in women (",
"      <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef80271 \" href=\"UTD.htm?14/52/15171\">",
"       figure 1",
"      </a>",
"      ). An HPV infection can also cause genital warts in women and men.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216804\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How can people get infected with HPV?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;People can get infected with HPV if they have sex with or touch the genitals of someone who is infected. People who have a lot of sex partners have a higher chance of getting an HPV infection.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216811\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of an HPV infection?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Most people do not have any symptoms when they get infected with HPV. And often, the infection will get better on its own. But in some people, the infection doesn&rsquo;t go away. People with a long-lasting HPV infection have a higher chance of getting cervical cancer or genital warts. These problems usually happen many years after a person is first infected.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216818\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Are different HPV vaccines available?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes, 2 different HPV vaccines are available. Girls and women can get either vaccine. Boys and men only get one type of HPV vaccine. Both HPV vaccines come in shots. Both involve getting 3 doses over 6 months.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216825\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       At what age do people get the HPV vaccine?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Most doctors recommend that girls get the HPV vaccine at age 11 or 12. But girls and women can get the vaccine any time from age 9 to 26. Women should not get the vaccine if they are pregnant. Boys can get the vaccine any time from age 9 to 26.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      The HPV vaccine works best when it is given before a person gets infected with HPV. The HPV vaccine can&rsquo;t cure an HPV infection that a person already has. That&rsquo;s why it is better to get the HPV vaccine before you have sex for the first time. If you have already had sex, talk with your doctor or nurse. He or she might recommend that you get the HPV vaccine anyway, because it could still help you.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216832\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What side effects can the HPV vaccine cause?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The HPV vaccine can cause redness, swelling, or soreness where the shot was given. It can also cause people to pass out, but this is uncommon. To make sure that this doesn&rsquo;t happen, your doctor or nurse will have you stay on the exam table for a few minutes after the shot.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216839\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Does the HPV vaccine always work?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The HPV vaccine is very good at preventing HPV infection and cervical cancer. But it is not perfect. In some cases, people who get the vaccine can still get an HPV infection.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216846\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Does the HPV vaccine prevent other diseases from sex?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;No. The HPV vaccine does not keep people from getting or spreading other diseases that are spread through sex. To keep from getting or spreading a disease that is spread through sex, you should use a type of protection called a condom.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2216853\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Do I need to be checked for cervical cancer if I get the vaccine?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. All women, including those who get the HPV vaccine, should be checked on a routine schedule for cervical cancer. Most women are checked using a test called a &ldquo;pap smear&rdquo; starting at age 21 or within 3 years of having sex for the first time.",
"     </p>",
